textResponse: Climate change is caused by humans and is affecting widespread negative consequences on the environment, wildlife, and humans.  It is causing extreme weather conditions and worsened natural disasters like hurricanes and wildfires.  A recent example is the Smokehouse Creek wildfire in Texas which consumed over a million acres and resulted in 2 human deaths and a large number of cattle deaths.   Climate change is causing drier conditions in some areas like Texas, and will make the risk of wildfires even greater.  The effect is moving eastward, so it's not just a problem for areas that have historically seen these problems; it will become more and more widespread.

In February, some years ago, our grid shut down. Even though I live in an affluent neighborhood, we couldn't go anywhere. The nearby hotel was full, and nowhere had a generator because nobody expected it to happen. My whole family lived in one room for a few days, by the fireplace that we couldn't keep going because of a lack of wood (I think it's gas powered or something). We'd go to the car sometimes to charge our phones and warm up, but showering wasn't an option. We got our power back in bouts––just enough to use the microwave for a minute or two. I remember how miserable it was. People less fortunate died. So many people died. And our congressman took himself to Cancun while people under his leadership––the leadership that led us to have a separate grid from the rest of the country in the first place––died.
